<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  Chapter 1 — What Is an Argument?
  Chapter 1 source for the PreTeXt vertical slice.

  Style conventions in use:
    <term> = first introduction of a technical term (italic + indexed)
    <em>   = emphasis only, used sparingly
    italics for word-mention vs. term-introduction:
      mention only       → <em>argument</em>
      term-introduction  → <q><term>valid</term></q>
    Quotes around quoted speech / example utterances → <q>...</q>
-->
<chapter xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="ch-what-is-an-argument">

  <title>What Is an Argument?</title>

  <introduction xml:id="ch-arguments-intro">
    <p>
      Spend ten minutes listening in any public space and you will notice
      people doing all sorts of things with language. They are telling
      stories, ordering food, complaining about traffic, complimenting
      each other's shoes, explaining how the parking app works, confessing
      crushes, lying about their weekends, asking for directions, and,
      even, on occasion, trying to convince someone of something using
      actual reasons.
    </p>
    <p>
      That last activity, the giving-reasons one, is what we'll call
      <term>making an argument</term>, and it is the subject of this book.
      The other activities are largely where we find and make meaning with
      each other, but arguments are special in their own way as well.
      Arguments let us ask: <q>is this any good?</q> You can't ask that of
      <q>good morning</q> or <q>could you pass the salt?</q> You can ask
      it of <q>Since data centers demand immense power, we must expand
      the electrical grid,</q> and the answer is not obvious until you
      stop and look closely (and might not be obvious even then).
    </p>
    <p>
      This book is about how to look closely.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-language">
    <title>What We Do With Language</title>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-catalog">
      <title>A short list of things we do with language</title>
      <p>
        Take all the things people do with language — every overheard
        sentence, every text, every email — and you can sort them, loosely,
        into a handful of types. The list isn't exact; many sentences do
        more than one thing at once, and philosophers of language have
        argued for a long time about exactly how the categories work. But
        for our purposes, a working list looks something like this.
      </p>
      <dl>
        <li>
          <title>Stating</title>
          <p>
            <q>It's raining.</q> <q>The library closes at nine.</q>
            <q>Data centers consume a lot of power.</q> Statements assert
            that something is the case. They can be true or false, and
            that is the property we are going to care about most.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Asking</title>
          <p>
            <q>What time is it?</q> <q>Did you eat already?</q> Questions
            request information. They aren't true or false themselves,
            even though their answers might be.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Commanding</title>
          <p>
            <q>Close the door.</q> <q>Show your ID.</q> Commands and
            requests try to get someone to do something. They're not
            true or false either, though there are good and bad ones.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Promising</title>
          <p>
            <q>I'll be there by seven.</q> <q>We'll consider your
            application by the fifteenth.</q> A promise commits the
            speaker to some future action. It's evaluable in its own
            way — promises are kept or broken — but not as true or false
            at the moment of speaking.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Expressing</title>
          <p>
            <q>Ouch.</q> <q>What a beautiful day.</q> Expressions report
            or perform an inner state. They're sincere or insincere,
            fitting or off-key, but again, not really true or false.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Performing</title>
          <p>
            Some sentences make something happen just by being said in
            the right circumstances. <q>I now pronounce you married.</q>
            <q>I name this ship the <em>Enterprise</em>.</q>
            <q>I apologize.</q> The philosopher J. L. Austin called these
            <term>performative</term> sentences and noticed they're a
            strange beast: they don't describe a marriage, a naming, or
            an apology — the act of uttering the right phrase under the
            right circumstances is just what it is to do the thing.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Greeting</title>
          <p>
            <q>Good morning.</q> <q>Hey.</q> <q>How's it going?</q> A
            great deal of human conversation is just acknowledging that
            other humans exist and are not strangers. The semantic
            content of <q>How's it going?</q> is roughly zero. The social
            work it does is enormous.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Explaining</title>
          <p>
            <q>The reason your phone is hot is that you've been on it
            for two hours.</q> <q>I'm late because there was an accident
            on Route 17.</q> Explanations look a lot like arguments —
            they offer reasons connected to a claim — and we'll come
            back to that resemblance later. For now just note that this
            distinction is a little tricky, but we'll want to pay
            attention to it.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Arguing</title>
          <p>
            <q>You shouldn't take Route 17 — there was an accident, and
            traffic is backed up to the next exit.</q> <q>We need to
            expand the grid because data centers are coming online faster
            than we can power them.</q> An argument offers reasons in
            support of a claim. The reasons are called <term>premises</term>,
            the supported claim is called the <term>conclusion</term>,
            and the relationship between them is mostly what the rest of
            this book is about.
          </p>
        </li>
      </dl>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-two-senses">
      <title>Two senses of <q>argument</q></title>
      <!--
        STYLE NOTE: Reno's revision uses italics-only for word-mentions
        of "argument", "argue", "arguing" here. This contrasts with the
        quotes+italics pattern used for "valid" and "sound" in the
        "What makes an argument good?" subsection below. We're keeping
        Reno's pattern as written; convention to be confirmed.
      -->
      <p>
        The word <em>argument</em> and its related verb forms
        <em>argue</em>, <em>arguing</em> are ambiguous in everyday
        English. They often refer to a verbal disagreement — two people
        exchanging insults, or yelling at each other about whether the
        runner was safe: <q>He was out!</q> <q>No way! He was safe!</q>
        That kind of dispute is not what we'll mean by <em>argument</em>
        in this book. We'll be using the word in the more specialized
        sense from the catalog above: an offering of reasons in support
        of a claim. From here on, when you see <em>argument</em>, that's
        the meaning to assume.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-persuading">
      <title>Persuading and arguing</title>
      <p>
        One thing you might notice in the list above is that I haven't
        said anything about <em>persuading</em>. That's deliberate.
        Persuasion isn't really a separate category — it's something a
        person can be trying to do across many of the categories at once.
        Importantly, you can persuade someone without arguing.
      </p>
      <p>
        Advertising is the cleanest example. Most ads don't make
        arguments. They show you a beautiful person enjoying a beautiful
        product in beautiful light, and they hope that you, watching,
        will associate the product with the feeling of beauty. There's
        no premise, no conclusion, no reasoning offered. There's just an
        emotional pairing. If you walk away from the ad wanting the
        product, the ad has succeeded — but it did not argue.
      </p>
      <p>
        Politicians do this too. So do friends, parents, salespeople,
        professors, and AI chatbots. A great deal of persuasion happens
        through repetition, charm, fear, social pressure, identity, and
        the sheer confidence with which a claim is delivered. None of
        this is arguing. None of it requires reasons.
      </p>
      <p>
        The reverse is also true. You can make a careful, airtight
        argument and persuade exactly nobody. Anyone who has tried to
        talk an unwilling family member out of a strongly held belief
        knows the experience.
      </p>
      <p>
        Logic is about the <em>reasoning</em> embedded in argumentative
        language, not about whether the reasoning works on its audience.
        Whether arguments persuade is, much of the time, a question of
        human psychology, and humans are persuaded by all sorts of things
        that have nothing to do with reasons. Whether arguments are
        <em>good</em> is a different question — a logical question — and
        it is the one we will spend the rest of this book learning to
        answer.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-good-argument">
      <title>What makes an argument good?</title>
      <p>
        The central observation of the opening was that arguments are
        the kind of language use about which we can ask, <q>is this any
        good?</q> You can ask other questions of other kinds of speech:
        whether a promise was kept, whether a question was relevant,
        whether an explanation was satisfying, whether a greeting was
        warm. But <q>is this argument any good?</q> is a question that
        implies a specific structure, and the structure implied by that
        question is what the rest of the book is for.
      </p>
      <p>
        What does it actually mean for an argument to be good?
      </p>
      <p>
        A first answer: a good argument is one whose conclusion really
        does follow from its premises. If the premises support the
        conclusion, then accepting the premises gives you reason to
        accept the conclusion. If the premises do not support the
        conclusion, the argument is bad — even if every sentence in it
        happens to be true. Bad reasoning can land on a true conclusion
        by accident; good reasoning can sometimes land on a false
        conclusion if the premises were false. Both happen all the time.
        This is because a good argument isn't just about truth and
        falsity.
      </p>
      <p>
        Logicians have a specific vocabulary for these properties. The
        word <q><term>valid</term></q> means roughly <q>the conclusion
        really does follow from the premises,</q> and it applies to the
        structure of an argument, not its content. And the word
        <q><term>sound</term></q> means <q>valid, and all the premises
        are also actually true.</q> For now, treat those as labels; we
        will fill in their precise meanings in the next chapter.
        The point is that those are the questions you can ask of an
        argument and not of sentences like <q>good morning</q> or
        <q>close the door.</q>
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-two-kinds">
      <title>Two kinds of arguing</title>
      <p>
        Arguments come in two broad kinds, and we'll discuss both in
        this book.
      </p>
      <p>
        Some arguments are <term>deductive</term>. In a deductive
        argument, the premises are supposed to guarantee the conclusion.
        A deductive argument asserts that if the premises are true, the
        conclusion has to be true too, no exceptions. If it's valid, and
        sound, then it works; it's a good argument. <q>All humans are
        mortal. Socrates is human. Therefore Socrates is mortal.</q> If
        you accept the premises, you can't dodge the conclusion without
        contradicting yourself. Most of Parts I, II, and III of this book
        are about deductive reasoning.
      </p>
      <p>
        Other arguments are <term>inductive</term>. In an inductive
        argument, the premises don't guarantee the conclusion, but they
        make it more likely than it would have been otherwise. Here's a
        <term>strong</term> inductive argument: <q>The last hundred
        flamingos I saw were pink. So the next flamingo I see will
        probably be pink too.</q> The conclusion isn't guaranteed even
        if the premises are all true; it's supported. Inductive arguments
        are the workhorses of science, statistics, medicine, and most
        everyday reasoning. Part IV of this book is about inductive
        reasoning, with statistical inference as its centerpiece.
      </p>
      <p>
        Both kinds count as arguing. Both can be done well or badly. The
        standards of <q>good</q> are different in each case — what makes
        a deductive argument good is not the same as what makes an
        inductive one good — but in both cases we can ask the same
        question we asked above: <q>is this argument any good?</q>
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-where-headed">
      <title>Where we're headed</title>
      <p>
        To talk about arguments precisely, we need vocabulary for their
        parts. Arguments are built out of <term>statements</term> —
        claims that are either true or false — combined in particular
        ways. Some statements serve as premises, some as conclusions,
        and in compound arguments some serve as both. Not all sentences
        are statements, though: greetings, questions, and commands
        aren't, as the list above suggests. The next section gets
        specific about what statements are and how to recognize them,
        because we can't say much about arguments without first saying
        what they're made of.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <exploration xml:id="field-1-1-1">
      <title>Field Exercise: Listen for ten minutes</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find a public space — a coffee shop, a hallway between classes,
          a bus stop, a dorm common area — and listen for ten minutes
          without participating. (You can pretend to be on your phone.
          Nobody will notice.)
        </p>
        <p>
          While you listen, try to spot the different kinds of language
          use from the catalog above. You don't have to be exact, and
          many things you hear will fit more than one category at once.
          Notice especially:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              How often you hear someone making an actual argument —
              that is, giving reasons in support of a claim.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Where the arguments tend to appear (between strangers,
              close friends, parents and kids, strangers with strong
              opinions about parking).
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Whether anything you heard sounded like an argument but,
              on second thought, was doing a different job — an
              explanation, a complaint, a vent, a recital of grievances.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          You don't have to write any of this down right now. The point
          is just to start noticing the difference. We'll come back to
          it in an end-of-chapter writing prompt, where you'll be asked
          to report and reflect on what you heard.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exploration>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-statements">
    <title>Statements</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        We can't talk carefully about arguments without being clear about
        what they are built out of. An argument is a structure — one or
        more statements offered in support of another statement — and
        every piece of that structure is a particular kind of sentence.
        Before we can do any actual logic, we need to be clear about what
        statements are and, just as importantly, what they are not.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-what-is-statement">
      <title>What a statement is</title>
      <p>
        A statement is an <term>assertoric</term> sentence — a sentence
        that says something is the case. The word <em>assertoric</em>
        comes from <em>assert</em>; an assertoric sentence is one that
        makes a claim about how things are. Every statement is either
        true or false.
      </p>
      <p>
        That definition is short, and we'll spend the rest of this
        section unpacking what it does and does not mean. But it is
        worth saying directly first.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-statement">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A <term>statement</term> is an assertoric sentence — a
            sentence that says something is the case. Every statement
            is either true or false.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        Only sentences in the <em>stating</em> category produce
        assertions. The other categories don't. Questions don't make
        claims about how things are; commands don't either; expressions
        and greetings and performatives are doing other work. None of
        those produce sentences that are true or false.
      </p>
      <p>
        A few examples of statements:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p><q>The library closes at nine.</q></p></li>
        <li><p><q>Snow is white.</q></p></li>
        <li><p><q>Carthage was destroyed in 146 BCE.</q></p></li>
        <li><p><q>Two plus two equals four.</q></p></li>
        <li><p><q>Data centers consume a great deal of electricity.</q></p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Each of these sentences claims that something is the case. Each
        is true or false. Most of them are also things almost nobody
        would push back on, and that's deliberate — we're starting with
        the easy cases.
      </p>
      <p>
        A few examples of sentences that are <em>not</em> statements:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p><q>What time is it?</q> (a question)</p></li>
        <li><p><q>Close the door.</q> (a command)</p></li>
        <li><p><q>Ouch.</q> (an expression)</p></li>
        <li><p><q>Good morning.</q> (a greeting)</p></li>
        <li><p><q>I now pronounce you married.</q> (a performative)</p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        None of these are statements, because none of them say that
        something is the case. None of them is true or false. They are
        doing other things with language, and those other things are
        valuable, but they aren't what arguments are built out of.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-harder-cases">
      <title>What about the harder cases?</title>
      <p>
        So far, so good. The examples above were chosen to be easy:
        nobody is going to fight you about whether the library closes
        at nine. But you may have already started to notice that real
        life isn't always like that. Sentences like <q>there is
        intelligent life somewhere else in the universe,</q> <q>slavery
        is wrong,</q> <q>there were exactly 27,891 people living in
        Fredericksburg in 1856,</q> and <q>the one-millionth digit of
        <m>\pi</m> is 7</q> all <em>seem</em> to be saying that
        something is the case. By the definition above, they should
        all be statements. But they don't feel like the library
        example. Some of them are deeply contested. Others involve
        facts nobody alive knows or can easily find out.
      </p>
      <p>
        Are they still statements?
      </p>
      <p>
        The short answer is yes. The longer answer requires getting
        clear on what is actually being asked. To handle the harder
        cases — the contested ones, the ones we can't easily, if at
        all, verify — we need to separate three things that often get
        smushed together: what is the case, what we <em>know</em>
        about what is the case, and what we <em>agree about</em> about
        what is the case. Once those three are pulled apart, the
        harder cases are no harder to classify than the library
        example.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-truth-knowledge-consensus">
      <title>Truth, knowledge, and consensus are different things</title>
      <p>
        What is the case is one thing. Whether anyone knows what is the
        case is another thing. Whether everyone agrees about what is
        the case is yet a third. These three are easy to run together
        in everyday speech, but they are genuinely separate, and
        statementhood depends only on the first.
      </p>
      <p>
        Consider a few examples in turn.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Things that are true or false even if we don't know which.</alert>
      </p>
      <p>
        There were exactly 27,891 people living in Fredericksburg on
        January 26th, 1856. Nobody alive knows whether that's true.
        The historical record isn't fine-grained enough to settle it.
        The sentence is still either true or false. The population of
        Fredericksburg, VA on January 26th, 1856 is a fact about the
        world; the sentence asserts that the number of people living
        here on that date was 27,891; the sentence is true if that was
        the number and false if it wasn't.
      </p>
      <p>
        There is intelligent life elsewhere in the universe. We don't
        know. We may never know. The sentence is still either true or
        false right now, today, regardless of what humans manage to
        find out in the next century or the next ten thousand years.
      </p>
      <p>
        The one-millionth digit of <m>\pi</m> is 7. Almost nobody has
        computed this. (For what it's worth, it's possible to look up;
        I haven't.) The sentence has a definite truth value at this
        moment, even for those of us who haven't checked.
      </p>
      <p>
        Caesar walked under a particular fig tree on the Ides of March,
        44 BCE. The world has not preserved that information for us.
        We can't recover it. The sentence is still either true or
        false; the world either was or wasn't arranged that way at
        that moment even though we don't know if it was or not.
      </p>
      <p>
        In each of these cases, the sentence is a statement, and for
        the same reason: there is a way the world was, or is, that the
        sentence makes a claim about. Whether <em>we</em> have access
        to that way the world was or is — whether anyone has computed
        it, recovered it from history, observed it, or proven it — is
        a different question. Statementhood depends on the first;
        knowledge is a question on top of it.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Things that are true or false even if we don't agree about which it is.</alert>
      </p>
      <p>
        Now consider a different kind of difficulty. <q>God exists.</q>
        Humans have been arguing about this sentence for as long as
        they've been arguing about anything. We have not settled it.
        The sentence is still either true or false. Whichever it is,
        the disagreement among humans does not change it.
      </p>
      <p>
        The same goes for <q>slavery is wrong,</q> <q>capital punishment
        is unjust,</q> <q>abortion is morally permissible in the first
        trimester,</q> and many other claims people have strong,
        divergent views about. These sentences make claims about how
        things are — about what is moral, what is just, what the world
        contains. Each is either true or false. Whether reasonable
        people agree is a separate question. Whether anyone can settle
        the disagreement is a third question. Neither is the same as
        whether the sentence is a statement. It is.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is the part that you might resist even if you buy the rest
        of this discussion. <em>Surely</em> if smart people disagree
        about a sentence, it must be that the sentence isn't really
        true or false — it must be that there's no fact of the matter,
        just a clash of preferences. That's not the assumption of
        classical logic, and it's not the assumption of this book.
        The assumption here is that disagreement and truth are
        different things. People can disagree about what's true.
        People can be wrong about what's true. None of that changes
        whether there's a fact of the matter, neither does it change
        that people are asserting something about the world when they
        utter these sorts of sentences.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Why this matters for what comes later.</alert>
        This isn't a philosophical sidebar. It's load-bearing structure
        for everything in the rest of the book. Truth tables work
        because every row has a definite truth value, regardless of
        what we happen to know about that row. Validity is a
        relationship between truth values. The reasoning we're going
        to teach you depends, all the way down, on the assumption that
        statements are either true or false — no matter who knows
        what, and no matter who agrees with whom.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-fact-vs-opinion">
      <title>The fact-vs-opinion taxonomy doesn't help</title>
      <p>
        Many of you were taught somewhere along the way to sort
        sentences into two bins: <em>facts</em> (which are true and
        provable) and <em>opinions</em> (which are subjective,
        debatable, and somehow not really claims about how things
        are). That taxonomy is not useful for logic. It is, in fact,
        actively in the way. This subsection is about why.
      </p>
      <p>
        Try a quick test on the distinction. Can there be false facts?
      </p>
      <p>
        Most people, asked cold, will say no. <em>Fact</em> in
        ordinary speech already means <q>true claim.</q> That's the
        whole point of saying <q>it's a fact</q> instead of just
        saying the thing. But notice what that concession costs the
        taxonomy. If the word <em>fact</em> already builds truth into
        itself, then <em>fact</em> cannot help us sort sentences
        before we have figured out what is true. The fact-vs-opinion
        taxonomy is asking us to grade the answers before we have
        read the questions.
      </p>
      <p>
        There's a second problem. Even sentences that everyone agrees
        with become <em>opinions</em> the moment somebody asserts
        them. If I say <q>two plus two equals four,</q> that's my
        belief — my opinion about how arithmetic works. It is also a
        fact. The same sentence is in both categories at once,
        depending on how you frame it. The categories don't pick out
        two different kinds of sentences; they collapse into each
        other on contact.
      </p>
      <p>
        A third problem. People sometimes use <em>opinion</em> in a
        looser sense — meaning something like <q>a claim that hasn't
        been settled.</q> On that usage, <em>opinion</em> names not a
        kind of sentence but a feature of how the conversation is
        going. That doesn't help us either. From the perfectly
        settled premises <q>2 + 5 = 7</q> and <q>3 + 4 = 7</q> you
        can build the argument <q>therefore (2 + 5) = (3 + 4).</q>
        It's a boring argument, but unmistakably an argument. Settled
        premises do not make a piece of reasoning stop being
        reasoning. And we already saw above that <em>unsettled</em>
        sentences — <q>God exists,</q> <q>slavery is wrong,</q> and
        the rest — are still statements. Settledness and statementhood
        have nothing to do with each other.
      </p>
      <p>
        So here is the replacement we want.
      </p>
      <principle xml:id="principle-statement-criterion">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The criterion for whether a sentence is a statement is not
            whether it is a <q>fact</q> or an <q>opinion.</q> It is
            whether the sentence is assertoric — whether it says that
            something is the case. If yes, it is a statement; it has
            a truth value; logic can operate on it. If no, it is some
            other kind of speech, and logic operates on it only
            indirectly, if at all.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </principle>
      <p>
        And, looking ahead one section, a related replacement: the
        criterion for whether something is an argument is also not
        whether the statements involved are facts or opinions. It is
        purely structural: some statements offered in support of
        another. We'll get to the details of that structure in the
        next section.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-where-headed-1-2">
      <title>Where we're headed</title>
      <p>
        Statements are the building blocks. The next section is about
        how those blocks fit together. What is a premise, technically
        speaking? What is a conclusion? What does it mean for one
        statement to support another? Once we have named those parts,
        we can start asking the question that drives the rest of the
        book: what makes one arrangement of statements a good argument
        and another arrangement a bad one. <em>Is this any good?</em>
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <exploration xml:id="field-1-2-1">
      <title>Field Exercise: Sort the sentences</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Below is a list of sentences. For each one, decide whether
          it is a statement (an assertoric sentence — one that says
          something is the case, and is therefore either true or
          false) or not.
        </p>
        <p>
          Use the definition from this section. Do not use the
          fact-vs-opinion taxonomy. Some of these sentences will
          tempt you to mis-sort them as <q>just opinions</q> or
          <q>not really statements.</q> Resist that temptation.
          Trust the definition.
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li><p>The library closes at nine.</p></li>
          <li><p>What time does the library close?</p></li>
          <li><p>Slavery is wrong.</p></li>
          <li><p>Pass the salt.</p></li>
          <li><p>There were exactly 27,891 people living in Fredericksburg in 1856.</p></li>
          <li><p>God exists.</p></li>
          <li><p>Chocolate ice cream is better than vanilla.</p></li>
          <li><p>Hey.</p></li>
          <li><p>There is no such thing as a false fact.</p></li>
          <li><p>The one-millionth digit of <m>\pi</m> is 7.</p></li>
          <li><p>We need to expand the electrical grid to keep up with new data centers.</p></li>
          <li><p>Ouch.</p></li>
        </ol>
        <p>
          For at least three of the sentences you sorted as
          statements, write a one-sentence explanation of why someone
          might mistakenly think they are <em>not</em> statements.
          We'll come back to this in the end-of-chapter writing
          prompt.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exploration>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-premises-conclusions">
    <title>Premises and Conclusions</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        In the previous section we said that arguments are built out of
        statements. Now we name the structural roles those statements
        play, and the relationship that makes a collection of statements
        an argument rather than just a list.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-premise-conclusion-defs">
      <title>What a premise is, what a conclusion is</title>
      <p>
        Every argument has two kinds of statement in it. There is the
        statement being argued for — the claim the argument is
        <em>for</em>. There are also the statements offered as reason
        to accept that claim. The first is the <term>conclusion</term>.
        The others are the <term>premises</term>.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-premise-conclusion">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A <term>premise</term> is a statement offered in support of
            another statement.
          </p>
          <p>
            A <term>conclusion</term> is the statement being supported.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        A small example.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-library-argument">
        <title>The library is closed</title>
        <statement>
          <p>P1: The library closes at nine.</p>
          <p>P2: It is now ten past nine.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: The library is closed.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        The symbol <m>\therefore</m> is read <q>therefore.</q> We won't
        use it constantly in prose, but you'll see it whenever an
        argument is laid out cleanly, and it's the symbol the proof
        checker we'll use later uses to mark the conclusion line.
      </p>
      <p>
        Two things to notice. First, an argument can have one premise
        or many. Most have several. Second, the conclusion is just
        another statement — there is nothing about its grammar or
        content that announces it as the conclusion. What makes it the
        conclusion is the <em>role</em> it plays in the argument: it's
        the claim the others are aiming at. The same sentence could be
        a premise in one argument and a conclusion in another,
        depending on what the arguer is trying to do.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-support-relation">
      <title>The support relation: intent and actuality</title>
      <p>
        When we say premises <em>support</em> a conclusion, we are
        saying two things at once, and it pays to keep them straight.
      </p>
      <p>
        The first is about the <alert>intent</alert> of the arguer.
        When somebody offers an argument, they are saying: <em>here are
        reasons; you should believe the conclusion because of them</em>.
        The premise/conclusion structure is built out of intent. If I
        say <q>It is ten past nine, so the library is closed,</q> I am
        claiming that the first sentence is reason to believe the
        second. Whether anyone <em>should</em> be persuaded is a
        different question.
      </p>
      <p>
        The second is about whether the support actually
        <alert>succeeds</alert>. The premises might genuinely give you
        reason to believe the conclusion (a good argument), or they
        might not (a bad argument). An argument can have its premises
        and its conclusion in their proper places, follow the rules of
        grammar, sound entirely persuasive — and still be a bad
        argument because the premises don't actually support the
        conclusion. A bad argument is still an argument. It's an
        argument whose support fails.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is the question we promised in <xref ref="sec-language"/>.
        <em>Is this any good?</em> Once we have premises and a
        conclusion in front of us, we can finally ask the question
        with an object in mind. Then, we can start to draw out some
        general properties from these specific arguments.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-indicator-words">
      <title>Indicator words</title>
      <p>
        In real texts, premises and conclusions are frequently flagged
        by short signal words. There's a small set of them that show
        up over and over, and recognizing them is half the work of
        recognizing arguments.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Conclusion indicators</alert> — words and phrases that
        flag what comes next as a conclusion:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p><em>therefore</em></p></li>
        <li><p><em>thus</em></p></li>
        <li><p><em>hence</em></p></li>
        <li><p><em>so</em> (when used inferentially)</p></li>
        <li><p><em>consequently</em></p></li>
        <li><p><em>it follows that</em></p></li>
        <li><p><em>which means that</em></p></li>
        <li><p><em>because</em></p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        <alert>Premise indicators</alert> — words and phrases that
        flag what comes next as a premise:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p><em>because</em></p></li>
        <li><p><em>since</em></p></li>
        <li><p><em>for</em> (when used inferentially)</p></li>
        <li><p><em>given that</em></p></li>
        <li><p><em>as</em></p></li>
        <li><p><em>the reason being</em></p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        A short example with both kinds of indicator:
      </p>
      <p>
        <q><em>Since</em> the library closes at nine, <em>and since</em>
        it is now ten past nine, the library is closed.</q>
      </p>
      <p>
        Two premise indicators (both <em>since</em>) flag the two
        premises. The unmarked sentence at the end is the conclusion.
      </p>
      <p>
        A caveat worth taking seriously. Indicator words play other
        roles or dual roles. <em>Because</em> often introduces a
        premise, but it can also introduce a <em>causal explanation</em>
        — a different kind of speech that can sound similar and which
        we'll work on distinguishing in the next section.
        <em>Because</em>, when it's used as a premise indicator, also
        tells you what the conclusion is that's being supported by
        that premise. For example, <q>You should support data center
        construction, because they are the most efficient way to fund
        public schools.</q> <em>Because</em> tells you both that
        <q>they are the most efficient way to fund public schools</q>
        is a premise and that <q>You should support data center
        construction</q> is the conclusion. <em>So</em> can introduce
        a conclusion (<q>It's late, so we should go home</q>) or it
        can be filler (<q>So, anyway, the cat got out</q>) without
        doing inferential work. Don't take an indicator as proof an
        argument is happening. Take it as a strong hint, then read
        carefully.
      </p>
      <p>
        And one more case. Sometimes there are no indicator words at
        all. A passage can have a perfectly clear argument without a
        single <em>therefore</em> or <em>because</em>. You then have
        to identify premise and conclusion by content and intent:
        which sentence is the claim the writer is asking you to
        accept, and which sentences are the reasons offered? That's
        a skill that takes practice. We'll begin that practice in
        the next section.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-standard-form">
      <title>Standard form</title>
      <p>
        Once we've picked premises and conclusion out of a passage, we
        lay them out cleanly. The convention we'll call
        <term>standard form</term> in this book goes like this:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p>Each statement is on its own line.</p></li>
        <li><p>Premises are labeled P1, P2, P3, <ellipsis/> in the order they appear.</p></li>
        <li><p>The conclusion is labeled C.</p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        When an argument has more than one conclusion (which happens
        often in real texts — see the section below on sub-conclusions),
        each conclusion gets a number (C1, C2, <ellipsis/>) and a
        parenthetical note saying which premises and earlier
        conclusions it follows from.
      </p>
      <p>
        Two worked examples now, both about the same general topic.
        They're worth pausing on, because together they make a point
        we'll return to throughout the book.
      </p>
      <p>
        Before we look at them, we need one piece of vocabulary that
        both examples use. Conditional sentences — sentences of the
        form <q>If [something], then [something else]</q> — have two
        named parts. The part following <em>if</em> is called the
        <term>antecedent</term>. The part following <em>then</em> is
        called the <term>consequent</term>. (In real text the
        <em>then</em> is often left implicit, but the structure is
        the same: <q>If it rains, the streets are wet</q> is doing
        the same work as <q>If it rains, then the streets are
        wet.</q>) We'll work with conditionals in much more detail in
        Part III; for now the labels are enough to follow the examples
        below.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-antecedent-consequent">
        <title>Identifying antecedent and consequent</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            In each of the following conditional sentences, the
            antecedent and consequent are labeled.
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                <q>If it is raining, then the streets are wet.</q>
                <mdash/> Antecedent: <q>it is raining.</q>
                Consequent: <q>the streets are wet.</q>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <q>If there is no God, then life is meaningless.</q>
                <mdash/> Antecedent: <q>there is no God.</q>
                Consequent: <q>life is meaningless.</q>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <q>If there is evil in the world, then God does not exist.</q>
                <mdash/> Antecedent: <q>there is evil in the world.</q>
                Consequent: <q>God does not exist.</q>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        The first is the argument we met at the end of
        <xref ref="sec-statements"/>:
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-modus-tollens-god">
        <title>An argument for God's existence</title>
        <statement>
          <p>P1: If there is no God, then life is meaningless.</p>
          <p>P2: Life is not meaningless.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: God exists.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        This argument has the structure logicians call
        <term>modus tollens</term>: from a conditional and the denial
        of its consequent, we conclude the denial of its antecedent.
        We'll meet this and other named argument forms in detail in
        Part III.
      </p>
      <p>
        The second argument draws the <em>opposite</em> conclusion
        from the same general territory:
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-modus-ponens-evil">
        <title>An argument against God's existence</title>
        <statement>
          <p>P1: If there is evil in the world, then God does not exist.</p>
          <p>P2: There is evil in the world.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: God does not exist.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        This argument has the structure called
        <term>modus ponens</term>: from a conditional and the
        affirmation of its antecedent, we conclude the affirmation of
        its consequent. Like modus tollens, we'll come back to it.
      </p>
      <p>
        These two arguments make opposite claims. They take opposite
        sides of one of the deepest, longest-running disputes in
        human thought. Yet structurally, both are perfectly fine
        argument <em>forms</em> — meaning that <em>if</em> their
        premises were true, their conclusions would have to be true
        too. The disagreement between them isn't a disagreement about
        logic. It's a disagreement about whether the premises hold:
        whether life is meaningful, whether evil exists in a sense
        that's incompatible with God. Settling those is hard work,
        much harder than checking the structure. But notice what the
        structural framing does for us: it makes it perfectly clear
        <em>where</em> the disagreement lies. The arguer who accepts
        the first argument and rejects the second is committed to
        defending <q>life is not meaningless</q> and challenging
        <q>if evil exists, God does not.</q> That's a real position
        to hold; it's also one a critic can engage with by attacking
        exactly those premises.
      </p>
      <p>
        Structure first. Then we can ask what's good about an
        argument and what isn't, and have a productive disagreement
        when we disagree.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-subconclusions-seed">
      <title>Many arguments have sub-conclusions</title>
      <p>
        Most real-world arguments are messier than P1, P2,
        <m>\therefore</m> C. Often a passage argues for an
        intermediate claim and then uses that claim as a premise for
        a further conclusion. When you see an argument laid out with
        C1, C2, and parenthetical notes like <em>(from P1 and P2)</em>
        or <em>(from C1 and P3)</em>, that's what's going on.
        Conclusions can themselves serve as premises for later
        conclusions, and complex arguments are stacks of inferences.
        We'll work with these explicitly in the next section and
        later. For now: don't be surprised when a real argument has
        more than one conclusion in it.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-where-headed-1-3">
      <title>Where we're headed</title>
      <p>
        We now have the parts (statements), the roles those parts
        play (premises, conclusions), the relationship between them
        (support, intended and actual), and the standard layout
        (standard form, with sub-conclusions where the argument is
        layered). What we don't yet have is much practice extracting
        all that from real text — text where the indicator words
        might be missing or misleading, where multiple things are
        happening at once, and where a passage that <em>looks</em>
        like an argument is sometimes really an <em>explanation</em>
        — a different kind of speech that uses the same shape.
        That's the next section. The eavesdropping field exercise
        from <xref ref="sec-language"/> is about to start paying off.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <exploration xml:id="field-1-3-1">
      <title>Field Exercise: Lay out the arguments in standard form</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For each passage below, identify the premises and the
          conclusion. Then write the argument in standard form (P1,
          P2, <ellipsis/> <m>\therefore</m> C). If a passage has
          indicator words, note which ones helped you. If it doesn't,
          write a one-sentence explanation of how you decided which
          statement was the conclusion.
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <q>Since data centers are coming online faster than we
              can power them, and since rolling blackouts are
              unacceptable in a modern economy, we need to expand the
              electrical grid.</q>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <q>Either we stop subsidizing oil or we accept that our
              climate goals are political theater. We are not going
              to accept that our climate goals are political theater.
              Therefore, we should stop subsidizing oil.</q>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <q>I shouldn't take the elective in graphic design. The
              course meets at eight in the morning. I have soccer
              practice that runs late on Mondays.</q>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <q>If the death penalty deterred crime, we would expect
              murder rates to be lower in states that have it than in
              states that don't. Murder rates are not lower in those
              states. So the death penalty does not deter crime.</q>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <q>We can't simply redesign assignments to prevent lazy
              AI use. If you ask students to use AI but critique what
              it spits out, they can generate the critique with AI.
              If you give them AI tutors trained only to guide them,
              they can still use tools that just supply the answers.
              And detectors are too prone to false accusations of
              cheating and too poor at catching lightly edited output
              for professors to rely on them.</q>
              (From Clay Shirky, <q>Students Hate Them. Universities
              Need Them. The Only Real Solution to the A.I. Cheating
              Crisis,</q> <em>The New York Times</em>, August 2025.)
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </exploration>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-recognizing-arguments">
    <title>Recognizing Arguments in the Wild</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        In the previous three sections we assembled the apparatus.
        Language does many jobs (<xref ref="sec-language"/>); only
        some sentences are statements (<xref ref="sec-statements"/>);
        arguments are statements arranged into premises and a
        conclusion connected by an inferential relation
        (<xref ref="sec-premises-conclusions"/>). We have what we need.
      </p>
      <p>
        The trouble is that our use of language doesn't come
        pre-labeled. Sentences flow into each other without indicator
        words, or with misleading ones. Two passages that look
        identical on the page can be doing entirely different jobs.
        Multiple arguments can be tangled together in one paragraph,
        with intermediate claims doing double duty as conclusions of
        one inference and premises of the next. Recognizing arguments
        in the wild — picking them out of real prose, distinguishing
        them from things that aren't quite arguments, laying them out
        so we can examine them — is the skill that turns the apparatus
        from something you can describe into something you can
        actually use. And that's our aim. The development of the
        skills needed to pick out and analyze arguments and the
        corresponding skills needed to produce good arguments. The
        answer to the question, <q>Is it any good?</q> is not idle.
        The answer is an active engagement with other people's
        language and your own.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-argument-or-explanation">
      <title>Argument or explanation?</title>
      <p>
        Way back in <xref ref="sec-language"/> we put
        <em>explaining</em> in the catalog of things people do with
        language and noted that explanations look a lot like
        arguments. They use reasons. They have inferential structure.
        They often use the same indicator words — especially
        <em>because</em>. They can sound, on a first reading, exactly
        the same. The difference is not in the words. It's in the job
        the words are doing.
      </p>
      <p>
        An argument moves you from claims you accept (the premises)
        to a claim that's in question (the conclusion). The conclusion
        is the thing the arguer is trying to get you to believe — the
        part you might not have accepted before. The premises are the
        reasons offered.
      </p>
      <p>
        An explanation works in the other direction. The thing being
        explained is something everyone (in the intended audience)
        already accepts — it's not in question. The explanation
        provides the reasons <em>why</em> that already-accepted thing
        is the case. You're not being asked to believe the
        explanandum; you already do. You're being told why it's true.
      </p>
      <p>
        (Two pieces of vocabulary, since you'll occasionally see
        them: the <term>explanandum</term> is the thing being
        explained; the <term>explanans</term> is the reason offered.
        <em>Premise</em> and <em>conclusion</em> are the parallel
        words for arguments.)
      </p>
      <p>
        The same content can serve as either an argument or an
        explanation, depending on what's in question.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-grid-argument-or-explanation">
        <title>Same claim, different jobs</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <alert>Argument.</alert> <q>We should expand the
            electrical grid, because data centers are being built
            faster than we can power them.</q>
          </p>
          <p>
            <alert>Explanation.</alert> <q>Electricity prices are
            rising, because data centers are being built faster than
            we can power them.</q>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        Same claim after <em>because</em>. In the first, the
        conclusion is <em>we should expand the grid</em> — a claim
        that's contested, that depends on policy and money, and that
        the speaker is trying to bring you around to. The premise is
        the reason offered: <em>data centers are being built faster
        than we can power them.</em> It's an argument because there's
        something at issue.
      </p>
      <p>
        In the second, the thing to be explained, the explanandum,
        is <em>electricity prices are rising</em>. That's not in
        question. Anyone's electric bill has been telling them this
        for a while. The work being done is to explain <em>why</em>.
        The data-center load isn't being offered as a reason to
        <em>believe</em> prices are rising; it's being offered as a
        reason <em>they are</em>. It's an explanation.
      </p>
      <p>
        Another pair, even clearer:
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-car-argument-or-explanation">
        <title>The car</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <alert>Argument.</alert> <q>Your car doesn't have any gas,
            so it won't start.</q>
          </p>
          <p>
            <alert>Explanation.</alert> <q>My car wouldn't start. Oh,
            look — I'm out of gas. That's why.</q>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        The first is prospective. It's not yet known that you won't
        be able to start your car. The speaker is reasoning forward
        from a known fact (no gas) to a predicted outcome (won't
        start). It's an argument.
      </p>
      <p>
        The second is retrospective. The car has already failed to
        start; that's the data point everyone has. The reason offered
        (out of gas) is offered to explain the already-observed fact.
        It's an explanation.
      </p>
      <p>
        That last contrast points to a useful diagnostic:
        <alert>arguments are often future- or contention-oriented;
        explanations are usually past- or already-accepted-oriented.</alert>
        It isn't a perfect rule. Some arguments are about the past —
        a historian arguing for one reconstruction of an event over
        another, for instance, is making an argument about something
        that already happened, but the conclusion is still in question
        because the <em>historical claim</em> hasn't been settled.
        And a few explanations gesture forward — <q>the storm will be
        bad because the air pressure is dropping fast</q> could be
        either, depending on whether the listener already accepts that
        the storm will be bad. But for a quick first pass,
        time-direction is a strong tell: when in doubt, ask whether
        the would-be conclusion is something the audience already
        believes (likely an explanation) or something the speaker is
        trying to convince them of (likely an argument).
      </p>
      <p>
        A second diagnostic worth keeping: <alert>argue or make sense
        of?</alert> If the speaker's posture is <em>let me convince
        you of this</em>, it's an argument. If it's <em>let me help
        you make sense of this</em>, it's an explanation. Same words
        on the page can do either job, depending on what kind of
        conversation is happening.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-extraction-procedure">
      <title>A procedure for extracting arguments</title>
      <p>
        Here is a workable procedure for pulling an argument out of
        real text. It looks pedantic written down, but it gets
        natural, nuanced, and requires judgment as you practice.
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Read the passage twice.</alert> Once for the gist;
            once ready to take notes.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Find the conclusion.</alert> Ask yourself: what is
            the writer asking the reader to accept? It's often — not
            always — the most contentious-sounding sentence in the
            passage. Look for conclusion indicators (<em>therefore,
            thus, so, hence, consequently</em>) but don't rely on
            them; conclusions can sit at the start of a passage, at
            the end, or in the middle.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Find the premises.</alert> Ask: what reasons are
            given for the conclusion? Look for premise indicators
            (<em>because, since, given that, for</em>) and for
            sentences whose role is clearly to support something
            else.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Lay it out in standard form</alert> (P1, P2,
            <ellipsis/> <m>\therefore</m> C). One statement per line.
            Use exactly the wording the passage uses where possible;
            reword only when the passage's prose makes the structure
            hard to see.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Check the structure.</alert> Does the conclusion
            really follow from the premises? Is something obviously
            missing — a hidden assumption the passage takes for
            granted? Are there actually two arguments in this passage
            instead of one? Does what looks like a single premise
            turn out to itself be a small argument?
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        A worked example. Here's a short paragraph:
      </p>
      <blockquote>
        <p>
          Most people think of running shoes as a recent invention,
          but archaeologists have found rope-soled sandals from twenty
          thousand years ago that show specific wear patterns
          associated with running, and similar sandals have appeared
          independently in widely separated cultures. So the
          deliberate design of footwear for running is a much older
          human practice than people assume.
        </p>
      </blockquote>
      <p>
        Read once for gist: claim about running-shoe history. Read
        again taking notes or marking up the passage: the conclusion
        is signaled by <em>so</em> — <em>the deliberate design of
        footwear for running is a much older human practice than
        people assume</em>. The premises are the two historical
        claims that are assumed to be true: the claims about
        archaeological discoveries and cultural distribution.
      </p>
      <p>
        In standard form:
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-running-shoes-standard-form">
        <title>Running shoes, in standard form</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            P1: Archaeologists have found rope-soled sandals from
            twenty thousand years ago with wear patterns associated
            with running.
          </p>
          <p>
            P2: Similar running-adapted sandals have appeared
            independently in widely separated cultures.
          </p>
          <p>
            <m>\therefore</m> C: The deliberate design of footwear
            for running is a much older human practice than people
            assume. <em>(from P1 and P2)</em>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        Two premises, one conclusion, indicator word <em>so</em>. The
        first sentence (<q>Most people think<ellipsis/></q>) isn't a
        premise of the argument; it's setting up what the argument is
        pushing back against. Notice that — sometimes the prose
        includes orientation that isn't part of the inference, and
        you should leave it out of the standard-form layout. Though,
        sometimes, this set-up is so integral to the argument that it
        will make it into the conclusion itself.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-layered-arguments">
      <title>Layered arguments and sub-conclusions</title>
      <p>
        In <xref ref="sec-premises-conclusions"/> we noted that real
        arguments are often messier than P1, P2,
        <m>\therefore</m> C. Sometimes a passage argues for an
        intermediate claim and then uses that intermediate claim as
        a premise for a further conclusion. We called these
        intermediate claims <term>sub-conclusions</term>. The
        notation: each sub-conclusion is labeled C1, C2,
        <ellipsis/> and followed by a parenthetical note saying
        which premises (and which earlier conclusions) it follows
        from.
      </p>
      <p>
        A worked example. Here's a paragraph adapted from a charity
        pitch:
      </p>
      <blockquote>
        <p>
          You should donate to Oxfam. Oxfam efficiently uses
          contributions to help end long-term poverty by providing
          the tools for people to get an education and support their
          families. Eighty-nine cents of every dollar goes directly
          to organizations on the ground. The aid provides for things
          like goats and schoolbooks, so that a family can provide
          for itself and the next generation has options. Also, it
          feels good to help people.
        </p>
      </blockquote>
      <p>
        The conclusion is the first sentence: <em>you should donate
        to Oxfam</em>. Notice the conclusion at the start, not the
        end — perfectly common. The rest of the paragraph is offering
        reasons.
      </p>
      <p>
        But the structure is layered. Some of the reasons are
        themselves supported by other reasons. Two factual claims
        (89 cents on the dollar; the aid provides for goats and
        schoolbooks) support an intermediate claim (Oxfam uses
        donations efficiently to end long-term poverty). That
        intermediate claim, plus a separate consideration (it feels
        good to help people), supports the main conclusion (you
        should donate). Laid out:
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-oxfam-standard-form">
        <title>Oxfam, in standard form</title>
        <statement>
          <p>P1: 89 cents of every dollar goes directly to organizations on the ground.</p>
          <p>P2: The aid provides for things like goats and schoolbooks.</p>
          <p>C1: The aid Oxfam provides makes it so a family can provide for itself and the next generation has options. <em>(from P2)</em></p>
          <p>C2: Oxfam efficiently uses contributions to help end long-term poverty by providing the tools for people to get an education and support their families. <em>(from P1 and C1)</em></p>
          <p>P3: It feels good to help people.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C3: You should donate to Oxfam. <em>(from C2 and P3)</em></p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        This is the diagramming notation we'll use throughout the
        book whenever an argument has more than one inference in it.
        Two things worth pausing on.
      </p>
      <p>
        First, every conclusion declares what it follows from.
        <em>(from P2)</em>, <em>(from P1 and C1)</em>, <em>(from C2
        and P3)</em> — those parenthetical notes are how the structure
        shows itself. Without them, a multi-step argument is just a
        list of statements, and the reader has to guess which
        inferences the writer intended.
      </p>
      <p>
        Second, this is harder than it looks the first time. The
        Oxfam paragraph contains six statements doing different jobs
        — two raw premises, three inferred claims (one of which is
        the final conclusion), and one independent premise (P3) that
        doesn't connect to the others until the very end. Pulling
        that structure out cleanly takes practice. The Field Exercise
        below has a couple of layered passages so you can practice on
        something a little messier than the one we just did together.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-where-headed-1-4">
      <title>Where we're headed</title>
      <p>
        That's the apparatus and the extraction skill. To recap what
        we've put together over four sections: the recognition that
        language does many jobs and only some of them count as
        arguing (<xref ref="sec-language"/>); the precise notion of a
        statement as a sentence that is either true or false,
        regardless of who knows or who agrees
        (<xref ref="sec-statements"/>); the structural roles of
        premise and conclusion, the distinction between intent and
        successful support, indicator words, and standard form
        (<xref ref="sec-premises-conclusions"/>); and now
        (<xref ref="sec-recognizing-arguments"/>) the practice of
        pulling all of that out of real text, distinguishing argument
        from explanation, and handling layered structure.
      </p>
      <p>
        What we <em>can't</em> yet do is evaluate the arguments we've
        extracted. We can lay one out cleanly and we can ask the
        question we've been pointing at since the beginning —
        <em>is this any good?</em> — but we don't yet have the tools
        to answer that question with rigor. That's what the next
        chapter is for. Once an argument is in standard form, we can
        begin to ask whether the support is genuine: whether the
        conclusion really follows from the premises (validity),
        whether the premises are actually true (soundness), and what
        we should make of arguments where one of those holds but not
        the other. The chapters that follow give us the technical
        machinery — categorical logic in Part II, sentential logic
        and natural deduction in Part III, statistical reasoning in
        Part IV — for answering <em>is this any good?</em> in
        different domains. But all of those machines run on the
        structures we've built here. Statements as truth-bearing
        sentences; arguments as premises supporting conclusions.
        That's the foundation.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <exploration xml:id="field-1-4-1">
      <title>Field Exercise: Extract and classify</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For each passage below:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              Decide whether the passage is making an argument,
              giving an explanation, or doing something else (and
              say which).
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              If it is an argument, lay it out in standard form,
              including any sub-conclusions.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              If it is an explanation, identify the explanandum and
              explanans.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              If it is something else, say what.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Don't worry about evaluating whether the arguments are good.
          We'll get to that in the next chapter. For now, the work is
          just to see the structure.
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <q>Since the data centers in this region pull more than
              ten percent of available capacity at peak, and since
              the grid was designed for a load profile from twenty
              years ago, brownouts during summer evenings are now
              nearly inevitable absent serious investment in
              transmission.</q>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <q>Roman concrete has lasted two thousand years in the
              worst possible conditions for ordinary cement: salt
              water, repeated tide cycles, freeze-thaw. We've finally
              figured out why. The Romans included unslaked lime in
              the mix, which reacts with seawater to produce calcium
              aluminum silicate, sealing the very cracks that destroy
              modern concrete.</q>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <q>I shouldn't take the elective in graphic design. The
              course meets at eight in the morning. I have soccer
              practice that runs late on Mondays, and I've never been
              able to drag myself out of bed for an early class after
              a late practice.</q>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <q>You should support the proposed expansion of the
              campus library. Studies of similar projects at peer
              institutions show measurable improvements in student
              retention. The current building was last renovated in
              1973 and lacks accessible study space for students with
              disabilities. The expansion is also cheaper now than it
              will be in ten years; construction costs are projected
              to rise faster than inflation. And the library is the
              one space on campus that serves every student,
              regardless of major.</q>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <q>In the medieval university, the lecturer typically
              read aloud from a manuscript while students copied the
              text. Movable type was nonexistent and books were
              scarce; an entire institution might own only a single
              copy of a given text. Centuries before the printing
              press, the most efficient way to distribute knowledge
              was to put it in a single voice and have everyone in
              the room write it down at once.</q>
              (Adapted from Clay Shirky, <q>Students Hate Them.
              Universities Need Them,</q> <em>The New York Times</em>,
              August 2025.)
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </exploration>

  </section>

  <conclusion xml:id="conclusion-ch1">
    <title>Chapter Summary</title>

    <p>
      This chapter introduced the basic apparatus for recognizing and analyzing arguments. The core ideas, section by section:
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>What We Do With Language (§1.1).</alert> Language serves many purposes — stating, asking, commanding, promising, expressing, performing, greeting, explaining, arguing — and most of them are not arguing. An argument is a special use of language in which reasons are offered in support of a claim. Arguing is not the same as persuading: persuasion aims to change someone's mind by any means; arguing offers reasons. An argument can persuade without being good, and a good argument can fail to persuade. This section also previews what makes an argument good (validity and soundness) and introduces the two main kinds of arguments: deductive (where the premises are intended to guarantee the conclusion) and inductive (where the premises are intended to make the conclusion probable).
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Statements (§1.2).</alert> Arguments are built out of statements — assertoric sentences that are either true or false. Whether a sentence is a statement does not depend on whether anyone knows it is true, whether anyone can prove it, or whether people agree about it. The familiar fact-vs-opinion taxonomy is unreliable as a test for statementhood: many sentences people dismiss as &quot;just opinions&quot; are genuine statements (true or false), and many sentences people call &quot;facts&quot; are also someone's opinion (a belief they hold). The useful distinction is not fact vs. opinion but statement vs. non-statement.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Premises and Conclusions (§1.3).</alert> Every argument has premises and a conclusion. The conclusion is the claim being supported; the premises are the reasons offered in support of it. Indicator words — <em>therefore</em>, <em>so</em>, <em>since</em>, <em>because</em>, among others — often flag premises and conclusions, but they are not always present and not always reliable. Standard form lays an argument out with each statement on its own line (P1, P2, ... <m>\therefore</m> C). A conditional sentence (&quot;If ..., then ...&quot;) has an antecedent (the &quot;if&quot; part) and a consequent (the &quot;then&quot; part). Two named argument forms were previewed: modus ponens (affirming the antecedent) and modus tollens (denying the consequent).
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Recognizing Arguments in the Wild (§1.4).</alert> Arguments and explanations can look identical on the page but do different work. An argument moves the audience from accepted premises to a conclusion that is in question. An explanation provides reasons why something already accepted is the case. Two diagnostics: (1) Is the would-be conclusion something the audience already accepts (likely explanation) or something the speaker is trying to convince them of (likely argument)? (2) Is the speaker's posture &quot;let me convince you&quot; (argument) or &quot;let me help you make sense of this&quot; (explanation)? Real-world arguments are often layered: intermediate claims (sub-conclusions) serve as premises for further inferences. Standard form uses C1, C2, etc. with parenthetical notes to show which premises and earlier conclusions each sub-conclusion follows from.
    </p>

  </conclusion>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch1-key-terms">
    <title>Key Terms</title>

    <p>Listed alphabetically, with section references.</p>

    <dl>
      <li xml:id="term-antecedent">
        <title>Antecedent</title>
        <p>In a conditional sentence (&quot;If ..., then ...&quot;), the part following &quot;if.&quot; (§1.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-argument">
        <title>Argument</title>
        <p>A set of statements in which one or more statements (the premises) are offered as reasons in support of another statement (the conclusion). (§1.1, §1.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-assertoric">
        <title>Assertoric</title>
        <p>Describing a sentence that says something is the case; i.e., a sentence that is either true or false. Statements are assertoric sentences. (§1.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-conclusion">
        <title>Conclusion</title>
        <p>The statement in an argument that the premises are offered to support. (§1.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-conclusion-indicator">
        <title>Conclusion indicator</title>
        <p>A word or phrase (e.g., <em>therefore</em>, <em>thus</em>, <em>so</em>, <em>hence</em>, <em>consequently</em>, <em>it follows that</em>) that often signals that what follows is a conclusion. (§1.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-conditional-sentence">
        <title>Conditional sentence</title>
        <p>A sentence of the form &quot;If ..., then ...&quot; The &quot;if&quot; part is the antecedent; the &quot;then&quot; part is the consequent. (§1.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-consequent">
        <title>Consequent</title>
        <p>In a conditional sentence, the part following &quot;then.&quot; (§1.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-deductive-argument">
        <title>Deductive argument</title>
        <p>An argument in which the premises, if true, are intended to guarantee the truth of the conclusion. (§1.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-explanandum">
        <title>Explanandum</title>
        <p>In an explanation, the thing being explained — the already-accepted fact whose cause or reason is being given. (§1.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-explanans">
        <title>Explanans</title>
        <p>In an explanation, the reason offered for why the explanandum is the case. (§1.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-explanation">
        <title>Explanation</title>
        <p>A use of language in which reasons are given for why something already accepted is the case. Distinct from an argument, which offers reasons for a claim that is in question. (§1.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-inductive-argument">
        <title>Inductive argument</title>
        <p>An argument in which the premises, if true, are intended to make the conclusion probable but not certain. (§1.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-modus-ponens">
        <title>Modus ponens</title>
        <p>An argument form: from a conditional and the affirmation of its antecedent, conclude the affirmation of its consequent. (§1.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-modus-tollens">
        <title>Modus tollens</title>
        <p>An argument form: from a conditional and the denial of its consequent, conclude the denial of its antecedent. (§1.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-performative-sentence">
        <title>Performative sentence</title>
        <p>A sentence that, when uttered in the right context, performs the action it describes (e.g., &quot;I hereby resign&quot;). Not a statement. (§1.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-premise">
        <title>Premise</title>
        <p>A statement offered in support of a conclusion. (§1.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-premise-indicator">
        <title>Premise indicator</title>
        <p>A word or phrase (e.g., <em>because</em>, <em>since</em>, <em>given that</em>, <em>for</em>, <em>the reason being</em>) that often signals that what follows is a premise. (§1.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-sound-argument">
        <title>Sound (argument)</title>
        <p>An argument that is valid and has all true premises. Previewed here; treated in detail in Chapter 2. (§1.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-standard-form">
        <title>Standard form</title>
        <p>A layout for arguments in which each statement appears on its own line, premises are labeled P1, P2, etc., and the conclusion is labeled C. Sub-conclusions are labeled C1, C2, etc. with parenthetical notes showing what each follows from. (§1.3, §1.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-statement">
        <title>Statement</title>
        <p>An assertoric sentence — a sentence that is either true or false, regardless of whether anyone knows which, can prove which, or agrees about which. (§1.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-strong-inductive-argument">
        <title>Strong (inductive argument)</title>
        <p>An inductive argument in which the premises, if true, make the conclusion highly probable. Previewed here; treated in detail in Part IV. (§1.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-sub-conclusion">
        <title>Sub-conclusion</title>
        <p>An intermediate conclusion in a layered argument that serves as a premise for a further inference. (§1.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-valid-argument">
        <title>Valid (argument)</title>
        <p>An argument in which, if all the premises were true, the conclusion would have to be true. Previewed here; treated in detail in Chapter 2. (§1.1)</p>
      </li>
    </dl>

  </section>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-ch1">
    <title>End-of-Chapter Exercises</title>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch1-s01">
      <title>Exercise Set 1: What We Do With Language</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each item below, identify the main thing the speaker is doing with language: stating, asking, commanding/requesting, promising, expressing, performing, greeting, explaining, or arguing. Some items may do more than one thing, but choose the dominant role and briefly explain your choice.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s01-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;Could you send me the reading before class?&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s01-02">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;The reading is posted on Canvas.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s01-03">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;I promise I'll bring the handouts tomorrow.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s01-04">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;Welcome back.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s01-05">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;I hereby resign from the committee.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s01-06">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;Yikes, that was loud.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s01-07">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;The room is cold because someone left the window open overnight.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s01-08">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;You should not park in that lot, because campus police ticket cars there every afternoon.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s01-09">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;The oldest tree on campus is more than seventy years old.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s01-10">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;Please silence your phone.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s01-11">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;I'll pick you up at seven.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s01-12">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;The senator's proposal will cost taxpayers more than it saves.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s01-13">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;You should take the bus to campus, since parking costs twelve dollars a day.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s01-14">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;The printer is jammed because someone loaded the wrong paper size.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s01-15">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;Congratulations on your promotion.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s01-16">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;Every student in this class passed the midterm.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <conclusion>
        <p>
          For the items you classified as arguments, identify the claim being supported and the reason offered in support of it. For the items you classified as explanations, identify what is being explained and what explains it.
        </p>
      </conclusion>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch1-s02">
      <title>Exercise Set 2: Arguing and Persuading</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each case below, decide whether the person is arguing, persuading without arguing, both arguing and persuading, or neither. Explain your answer in one or two sentences.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s02-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A campus poster shows smiling students studying under trees and says, &quot;Choose UMW.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s02-02">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A friend says, &quot;You should come to the lecture because the speaker works on exactly the topic you wrote about last week.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s02-03">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A commercial repeats a restaurant's jingle five times but gives no reason to eat there.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s02-04">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A student says, &quot;I know this policy is unpopular, but it will reduce wait times and make advising appointments easier to schedule, so we should adopt it.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s02-05">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A coach says, &quot;Again. Run it again.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s02-06">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A politician says, &quot;This plan is patriotic, hopeful, and bold,&quot; but gives no reasons for thinking it will work.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s02-07">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A university email says, &quot;Register by Friday to avoid a late fee. Registration after Friday incurs a $50 surcharge.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s02-08">
        <statement>
          <p>
            An influencer posts a photo of themselves wearing a brand's clothing, with no caption other than the brand's hashtag.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s02-09">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A classmate says, &quot;Trust me, this professor is great,&quot; without giving any reasons.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s02-10">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A letter to the editor says, &quot;The city should fund the new shelter because homelessness has increased 30% and the current facility cannot accommodate everyone who needs help.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <conclusion>
      </conclusion>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch1-s03">
      <title>Exercise Set 3: Statements and Non-Statements</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each sentence below, decide whether it is a statement. If it is a statement, write &quot;statement&quot; and briefly say what it asserts. If it is not a statement, identify what kind of language use it is.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s03-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;The registrar's office opens at eight.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s03-02">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;Does the registrar's office open at eight?&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s03-03">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;Please bring your laptop to class.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s03-04">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;Factory farming is wrong.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s03-05">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;There were exactly 19 students in this room at 10:02 a.m. yesterday.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s03-06">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;Wow.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s03-07">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;Pineapple belongs on pizza.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s03-08">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;I now declare this meeting adjourned.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s03-09">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;No one knows how many grains of sand are on this beach.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s03-10">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;There are more than one million grains of sand on this beach.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s03-11">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;Wealth taxes are just.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s03-12">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;See you later.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s03-13">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;I doubt it will rain today.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s03-14">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;Would you like coffee or tea?&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s03-15">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;Climate change is the most urgent crisis of our time.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s03-16">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;Let's go.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <conclusion>
        <p>
          After sorting all sixteen, choose two statement examples that someone might mistakenly call &quot;just opinions.&quot; Explain why they are still statements according to the definition in Chapter 1.
        </p>
      </conclusion>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch1-s04">
      <title>Exercise Set 4: Truth, Knowledge, and Consensus</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each sentence below, answer three questions:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><p>Is the sentence a statement?</p></li>
          <li><p>Is the difficulty mainly about knowledge, consensus, both, or neither?</p></li>
          <li><p>Why does that difficulty not settle whether the sentence is a statement?</p></li>
        </ul>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s04-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;There are an even number of stars in the Milky Way.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s04-02">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;Universal basic income would make society fairer.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s04-03">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;The best possible grading system is contract grading.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s04-04">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;The first person to cross the Rappahannock River on January 1, 1900 wore a hat.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s04-05">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;Seven plus five equals twelve.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s04-06">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;There were exactly 412 people inside this stadium at 2:14 p.m. last Saturday.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s04-07">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;Abolishing standardized tests would make college admissions fairer.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s04-08">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;The campus bookstore opens at ten.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s04-09">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;The painting in the hallway was hung crooked at exactly 3:15 p.m. last Tuesday.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s04-10">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;Democracy is the best form of government.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s04-11">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;It is wrong to eat animals.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s04-12">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;Some planet outside our solar system has liquid water on its surface.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <conclusion>
      </conclusion>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch1-s05">
      <title>Exercise Set 5: Fact, Opinion, and Statementhood</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          The following classifications use the fact-vs-opinion taxonomy. For each one, explain what is wrong or incomplete about the classification from the point of view of Chapter 1.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s05-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;Factory farming is wrong&quot; is not a statement because it is an opinion.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s05-02">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;Seven plus five equals twelve&quot; is a fact, so it cannot be anyone's opinion.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s05-03">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;Universal basic income would make society fairer&quot; is not true or false because people disagree about it.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s05-04">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;There are an even number of stars in the Milky Way&quot; is not a statement because no one knows whether it is true.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s05-05">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;The campus bookstore opens at ten&quot; is a statement, but &quot;wealth taxes are just&quot; is not, because only the first one can be proven.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s05-06">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;No claim can be both false and useful&quot; cannot be used in an argument because it is about claims rather than about the world.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s05-07">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;The claim that 'we should raise the minimum wage' is just an opinion, so it cannot be a premise in an argument.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s05-08">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;'The Earth orbits the Sun' is a fact, not a statement.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s05-09">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;'Pineapple belongs on pizza' is neither true nor false because it is a matter of taste.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s05-10">
        <statement>
          <p>
            &quot;You can't argue about morality because moral claims are just opinions.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <conclusion>
      </conclusion>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch1-s06">
      <title>Exercise Set 6: Premises, Conclusions, and Indicators</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each passage below:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><p>Identify the conclusion.</p></li>
          <li><p>Identify the premise or premises.</p></li>
          <li><p>Note any indicator words.</p></li>
          <li><p>Lay the argument out in standard form.</p></li>
        </ul>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s06-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Since the printer is out of toner and the handout is due in ten minutes, we need to send the file electronically.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s06-02">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The university should add more evening classes. Many students work during the day, and evening sections would make it easier for them to graduate on time.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s06-03">
        <statement>
          <p>
            We should not rely on the app's arrival time estimate, because it has been wrong three times this week.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s06-04">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If the grant deadline is Friday, then the application must be submitted this week. The grant deadline is Friday. Therefore, the application must be submitted this week.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s06-05">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Either the department hires another advisor or students will keep waiting weeks for appointments. Students should not have to wait weeks for appointments. So the department should hire another advisor.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s06-06">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The city should repair the sidewalks near campus. The cracked pavement is a hazard for wheelchair users, and several students have already reported injuries.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s06-07">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The museum should extend its hours on weekends. Families with school-age children can only visit on Saturdays and Sundays, and the museum currently closes at three, which is too early for most families.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s06-08">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Because the forecast calls for freezing rain, and because freezing rain makes the roads dangerous, you should leave early for your drive.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s06-09">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If tuition increases, then more students will take on debt. Tuition is increasing. Therefore, more students will take on debt.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s06-10">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The dining hall should offer more vegetarian options. A recent survey shows that 28% of students want vegetarian meals, but only 10% of the menu is vegetarian.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s06-11">
        <statement>
          <p>
            We cannot trust the poll results, since the sample was not random and fewer than 200 people responded.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s06-12">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Either the committee approves the budget by Friday or the project will be delayed. The committee will not approve the budget by Friday. So the project will be delayed.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <conclusion>
      </conclusion>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch1-s07">
      <title>Exercise Set 7: Standard Form Without Indicator Words</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Each passage below contains an argument, but the indicator words are missing or minimal. Identify the conclusion by asking what the speaker is trying to get the reader to accept. Then lay the argument out in standard form.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s07-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            I am not signing up for the 8 a.m. section. My shift ends at midnight on Tuesdays, and I never sleep well after closing.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s07-02">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The final exam should be optional. The course already has three papers, two quizzes, and a presentation.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s07-03">
        <statement>
          <p>
            That road will flood again this spring. The drainage ditch is still blocked, and every heavy rain last year covered the intersection.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s07-04">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The club should meet in the student center instead of the dining hall. The dining hall is too loud for discussion. The student center has reservable meeting rooms.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s07-05">
        <statement>
          <p>
            We should take the train to D.C. Parking downtown is expensive, and the station is only a ten-minute walk from the museum.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s07-06">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The library needs more group study rooms. Every room is booked solid by Tuesday each week, and students end up working in the hallways.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s07-07">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The scholarship deadline should be extended. The financial aid office did not send the announcement until three days before it was due.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s07-08">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Campus parking is not the solution to our commuting problem. A single parking space costs the university $15,000 to build, and demand will always outpace supply.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s07-09">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The student government should publish its meeting minutes online. Currently, only people who attend the meetings know what was discussed.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s07-10">
        <statement>
          <p>
            This course should count toward the writing requirement. Every major assignment requires sustained analytical writing, and students regularly produce fifteen or more pages of revised prose.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <conclusion>
        <p>
          For two of your answers, add one sentence explaining how you recognized the conclusion without relying on an indicator word.
        </p>
      </conclusion>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch1-s08">
      <title>Exercise Set 8: Conditional Sentences</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each conditional sentence, identify the antecedent and the consequent.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s08-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If it rains, then the sidewalks will be wet.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s08-02">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If the server is down, then students cannot submit the quiz.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s08-03">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If the argument is sound, then it is valid.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s08-04">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If the archive is closed on weekends, then we cannot inspect the letters on Saturday.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s08-05">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If the grant is approved, then the lab will replace its oldest equipment.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s08-06">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If the campus expands housing, then more students will be able to live near their classes.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s08-07">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If the premise is false, then the argument is not sound.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s08-08">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If the bill passes, then tuition will not increase next year.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s08-09">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If the experiment is not replicated, then the results should be treated with caution.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s08-10">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If voter turnout increases, then the election results better reflect public opinion.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s08-11">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If the bridge is closed, then commuters will need an alternate route.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s08-12">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If all the premises of an argument are true and the argument is valid, then the conclusion is true.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <conclusion>
        <p>
          Then write two original conditional sentences of your own and label the antecedent and consequent in each.
        </p>
      </conclusion>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch1-s09">
      <title>Exercise Set 9: Modus Ponens and Modus Tollens</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each argument below:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><p>Put the argument in standard form if it is not already.</p></li>
          <li><p>Identify whether it has the form of modus ponens, modus tollens, or neither.</p></li>
          <li><p>Name the conditional premise's antecedent and consequent.</p></li>
        </ul>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s09-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If the alarm is armed, then opening the door will trigger it. The alarm is armed. Therefore, opening the door will trigger it.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s09-02">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If the greenhouse were heated, the tropical plants would still be alive. The tropical plants are not alive. Therefore, the greenhouse was not heated.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s09-03">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If the sculpture were made of bronze, then it would not be attracted to a magnet. The sculpture is attracted to a magnet. Therefore, the sculpture is not made of bronze.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s09-04">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If the river rises above the walkway, then the race will be rerouted. The river is rising above the walkway. So the race will be rerouted.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s09-05">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If the course required a textbook, it would appear on the bookstore list. The course does not require a textbook. Therefore, it does not appear on the bookstore list.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s09-06">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If the proposal reduces advising delays, then we should consider adopting it. We should consider adopting it. Therefore, the proposal reduces advising delays.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s09-07">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If class is canceled, then the assignment deadline will be extended. Class is canceled. Therefore, the assignment deadline will be extended.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s09-08">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If the building meets the fire code, then the sprinkler system is functional. The sprinkler system is not functional. Therefore, the building does not meet the fire code.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s09-09">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If the study abroad program requires a 3.0 GPA, then students below 3.0 are ineligible. The program requires a 3.0 GPA. Therefore, students below 3.0 are ineligible.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s09-10">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If the restaurant passed its health inspection, then the kitchen is clean. The restaurant passed its health inspection. Therefore, the restaurant is a good place to eat.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <conclusion>
      </conclusion>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch1-s10">
      <title>Exercise Set 10: Argument or Explanation?</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each passage below, classify it as an argument, an explanation, or something else. If it is an argument, identify the conclusion and premises. If it is an explanation, identify the explanandum and explanans. If it is something else, say what it is doing.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s10-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The coffee tastes bitter because the grounds were over-extracted.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s10-02">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The grounds were over-extracted, so the coffee will probably taste bitter.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s10-03">
        <statement>
          <p>
            You should bring an umbrella because the forecast calls for thunderstorms.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s10-04">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The fire alarm went off because smoke from the kitchen reached the detector.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s10-05">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Since the fire alarm is going off, we should leave the building.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s10-06">
        <statement>
          <p>
            My laptop is slow because I have twenty-seven browser tabs open.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s10-07">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Since this laptop cannot run the required software, you should use a computer lab machine for the assignment.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s10-08">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Welcome back. Did you finish the reading?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s10-09">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The Wi-Fi is slow because too many devices are connected to the network.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s10-10">
        <statement>
          <p>
            You should switch to the earlier section, since the later one conflicts with your work schedule.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s10-11">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The pipes froze because the thermostat was set too low overnight.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s10-12">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Have a good weekend.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <conclusion>
        <p>
          For two of the cases, explain how the same word, such as &quot;because&quot; or &quot;since,&quot; can appear in passages doing different jobs.
        </p>
      </conclusion>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch1-s11">
      <title>Exercise Set 11: Extracting Arguments From Realistic Prose</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each passage below, use the procedure from Section 1.4:
        </p>
        <p>
          1. Read for the gist.
        </p>
        <p>
          2. Find the conclusion.
        </p>
        <p>
          3. Find the premises.
        </p>
        <p>
          4. Lay the argument out in standard form.
        </p>
        <p>
          5. Check whether anything should be left out because it is background, orientation, or a separate language use.
        </p>
        <p>
          Do not evaluate the argument yet.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s11-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Most students think office hours are only for emergencies, but that is a mistake. Students should visit office hours early in the semester. Early visits make it easier to ask for help later, and they give professors a better sense of what students are finding confusing.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s11-02">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The city should add protected bike lanes on the road next to campus. Cars regularly pass cyclists with less than three feet of space, and the current painted lane disappears at the busiest intersection. A protected lane would make commuting safer for students and staff.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s11-03">
        <statement>
          <p>
            We should replace the old projector in Monroe Hall. It cuts out during class, the replacement bulbs are no longer easy to order, and several instructors have stopped using media clips because they cannot trust the equipment.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s11-04">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The policy should be revised before next semester. It was written before online advising appointments became common, and it does not say who is responsible when a student misses a remote meeting because of a technology failure.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s11-05">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The committee should not postpone the vote again. Everyone has had the proposal for three weeks. The remaining objections are about implementation details, not about the main principle, and those details can be handled after approval.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s11-06">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The campus shuttle schedule should be revised. The current routes were designed five years ago, before the new science building opened on the south end of campus. Students now have to walk twenty minutes from the nearest shuttle stop to reach their labs, and several have reported being late to class as a result.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s11-07">
        <statement>
          <p>
            College athletes should be allowed to profit from their name, image, and likeness. They generate millions in revenue for their schools, and other students are free to earn money from their talents.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s11-08">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The university should not eliminate the foreign language requirement. Research consistently shows that studying a second language improves cognitive flexibility. Many employers prefer candidates who speak more than one language. And exposure to another language and culture is part of what a liberal arts education is for.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s11-09">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Standardized test scores should be optional in admissions. Scores correlate more strongly with family income than with college performance, and many high-performing students test poorly due to anxiety.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s11-10">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The department should keep offering the senior seminar in person rather than moving it online. The seminar depends on spontaneous discussion, and online formats make it harder for students to build on each other's comments in real time.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <conclusion>
      </conclusion>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch1-s12">
      <title>Exercise Set 12: Layered Arguments and Sub-Conclusions</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Each passage below contains a layered argument. Lay it out in standard form using P1, P2, C1, C2, and so on. Include parenthetical notes saying what each conclusion follows from.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s12-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The university should expand evening tutoring. Many students who need tutoring work during the day. Students who work during the day cannot attend most current tutoring sessions. So the current schedule excludes many of the students who need help. Expanding evening tutoring would make academic support available to more students.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s12-02">
        <statement>
          <p>
            We should move the club meeting to Thursday. The room is already reserved for another group on Wednesday, so we cannot meet in our usual room then. If we meet somewhere else on Wednesday, several members will not know where to go. Thursday is the only night this week when the usual room is available.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s12-03">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The city should install better lighting near the crosswalk. Drivers often fail to see pedestrians there at night. Poor visibility makes collisions more likely. Better lighting would improve visibility, and improving visibility would make the crosswalk safer.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s12-04">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The department should keep the methods course as a requirement. Students who take it write stronger senior theses, because the course teaches research design before students begin independent projects. Stronger senior theses make the major more valuable. A required methods course also gives transfer students a shared foundation with students who began the major earlier.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s12-05">
        <statement>
          <p>
            We should not use attendance software that tracks students' locations. The software collects sensitive data. Sensitive data can be misused or exposed in a breach. Tools that create serious privacy risks should be avoided unless they are necessary. This software is not necessary, since professors can take attendance without location tracking.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s12-06">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The city should build a new park near the university. The nearest park is two miles away, and students without cars cannot easily reach it. A nearby park would improve mental health, because access to green space reduces stress. Reduced stress leads to better academic performance.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s12-07">
        <statement>
          <p>
            We should require all first-year students to take a critical thinking course. Students arrive with widely varying reasoning skills. A shared course would give everyone a common vocabulary for evaluating arguments. A common vocabulary makes class discussions in other courses more productive. More productive discussions improve learning across the curriculum.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s12-08">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The software should be replaced. It crashes at least once per week during peak hours. Each crash disrupts service for roughly 500 users. Frequent disruptions erode trust in the system. A system that users do not trust will not be used, and a system that is not used wastes the money spent on it.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <conclusion>
      </conclusion>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch1-s13">
      <title>Exercise Set 13: Mixed Review</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each passage below, complete all tasks that apply.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><p>Classify the passage as an argument, explanation, or another language use.</p></li>
          <li><p>Identify all statements in the passage.</p></li>
          <li><p>If it is an argument, put it in standard form.</p></li>
          <li><p>If it is an explanation, identify the explanandum and explanans.</p></li>
          <li><p>If it includes a conditional, identify its antecedent and consequent.</p></li>
          <li><p>If it includes a sub-conclusion, label it.</p></li>
        </ul>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s13-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If the storm reaches campus before noon, then afternoon labs should be canceled. The storm is projected to arrive by 11:30, so afternoon labs should be canceled.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s13-02">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The lab smelled strange because someone left a burner on after class.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s13-03">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Please do not leave burners on after class.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s13-04">
        <statement>
          <p>
            We should not schedule the exam on the Monday after break. Many students travel that weekend, and travel delays would make the exam harder for reasons unrelated to course learning.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s13-05">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If the collaboration policy applies to group chat notes, then students must list those notes in their acknowledgments. The collaboration policy does apply to group chat notes. Therefore, students must list those notes in their acknowledgments.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s13-06">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Students must list group chat notes in their acknowledgments because the collaboration policy applies to them.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s13-07">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The classroom was moved because the projector broke. The new classroom is in Combs.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s13-08">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Since the current policy does not mention online quizzes, students and instructors are interpreting it differently. If a policy is being interpreted differently by the people governed by it, then it should be clarified. Therefore, the current policy should be clarified.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s13-09">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If the committee meets on Friday, then the proposal will be voted on before the deadline. The proposal will not be voted on before the deadline. Therefore, the committee is not meeting on Friday.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s13-10">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The concert was canceled because the headlining band's bus broke down on the interstate.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s13-11">
        <statement>
          <p>
            You should apply for the internship. The application deadline is next week, the position pays well, and it is directly related to your major.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s13-12">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Since the fire alarm sometimes malfunctions, we cannot always tell from the alarm alone whether there is an actual fire. But since we cannot always tell, and since the cost of ignoring a real fire is catastrophic, we should treat every alarm as real until confirmed otherwise.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <conclusion>
      </conclusion>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch1-s14">
      <title>Exercise Set 14: Short Writing Prompts</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Choose two of the following prompts. Each response should be one to two paragraphs.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s14-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Describe a case where someone persuaded you without giving an argument. What made the persuasion work?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s14-02">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Describe a case where someone gave you an argument that did not persuade you. What were the premises and conclusion?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s14-03">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find a short passage from a news article, opinion piece, advertisement, syllabus, campus email, or social media post. Classify it as an argument, explanation, or something else. Defend your classification.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s14-04">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Return to the listening exercise from Section 1.1. Report one example of language use you noticed and classify it using the categories from the chapter.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s14-05">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Explain why &quot;statement&quot; is a more useful category for logic than &quot;fact&quot; or &quot;opinion.&quot;
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s14-06">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Write your own short layered argument with at least two premises, one sub-conclusion, and one final conclusion. Then lay it out in standard form.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s14-07">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Pick one of the arguments you put in standard form in Exercise Sets 6 or 7. Without yet using the formal tools from later chapters, write a paragraph assessing whether you think the premises actually support the conclusion. What would someone who disagrees with the conclusion say about the premises?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch1-s14-08">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find a passage from a textbook in another course you are taking. Determine whether the passage is making an argument, giving an explanation, or doing something else. Quote the passage, classify it, and explain your reasoning.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <conclusion>
      </conclusion>
    </exercisegroup>

  </exercises>

</chapter>
